.\" Manpage for custom _printf.
.TH man 1 "31 Mar 2023" "1.0" "_printf man page"
.SH NAME
_printf -\ formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #included "main.h"

.B int _printf(const char *
.I format
.B , ...)
.SH Description 
.B _printf()
Prints to standart output under the control of a
.I format
string that specefies how subsequent arguments are converted for output.
.SH Return Value
Upon succesful return this function return the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte used to end output to strings).

IF an output error is encountered, a negative value is returned.
.Sh Format of the format string
The format string is composed of zero o more directives: ordinary character (not %), which are copied unchanged to the output stream; and conversion  specefications, each of which results in fetching zero or more subsequent arguments. By default, the arguments are used in the order given.
.SH The conversion specifier 
A character that specifies the type of conversion toi be applied. the conversion specifiers are:
.TP
.B d, i
The int argument is converted to sigmned decimal notation.
.TP . c 
The int argument is converted to an  unsigned char, and the resulting character is written.
.B s
The conts char * argument is expected to be a pointer to an array of characters type (pointer to a string). Characters from the array are written up (but not including) a terminating null byte('\0').
.B %
A '%' is written but no argument is converted. The complete version of specification is '%%'
.SH EXAMPLE
To print the day of the year, where weekday and month are pointers to string and day and year are integers:

#include "main.h"

_printf("%s, %s %d, %d\\n", weekday, month, day, year);
.SH SEE ALSO
.I printf (3)
.SH AUTHOR
Yaniel Ramos, Miguel De Jesus
